# Swift Performance Auditing (profiling-first)

When asked to “optimize performance”, do a **structured perf audit** and report each finding as:
- **Hotspot**, **Symptom**, **Evidence** (metric + tool), **Root cause**, **Fix**, **Before/after**.

## Measurement rules (don’t guess)

- Prefer **Instruments**: Time Profiler, Allocations, Leaks, Main Thread Checker, Points of Interest.
- Capture **device + build config** (Debug/Release) and **repro steps** for the slowdown.
- Validate optimizations in **Release** when relevant (optimizer can change behavior/perf).

## High-signal audit targets (triage in this order)

- **Main-thread work**: sync I/O, JSON decode, image decode/resize, crypto, large layout work.
- **Allocations/retains**: excessive temporary arrays/strings, bridging churn, repeated formatter creation.
- **ARC/retain cycles**: long-lived closures, delegates, timers, observers (leaks → jank).
- **Concurrency “task storms”**: unbounded `Task {}` fan-out, missing cancellation, chatty cross-actor hops.
- **SwiftUI invalidation**: expensive work in `body`, unstable identities, models recreated each render.

## Swift Concurrency audit prompts

- Identify where tasks are created; ensure **structured concurrency** and explicit limits.
- Check cancellation paths (`Task` handles, `onDisappear`, `deinit`, `withTaskCancellationHandler`).
- Minimize cross-actor hops on hot paths; isolate state so most work stays on one executor.

## SwiftUI audit prompts

- Ensure expensive derived data isn’t recomputed in `body`; move to model or memoize.
- Verify stable identity (`id`) in lists; avoid recreating reference models (use `@StateObject` when owned).

## Evidence to include in reports

- A concrete metric (CPU time, alloc count/bytes, frame drops, app hang duration).
- A stack trace / symbol / file+function pointing to the hotspot.
- A before/after comparison and how it was measured.
